5. He has made a peace with them who have slaine the servants of the Lord with a rage that reacheth unto heaven: and that these execrable Villaines may doe the like service in England, they are called over hither. The Lord bring the man that has done all this into the deeps for all this▪ that one deep may call upon another deep; that he may humble himselfe greatly before the God of his Fathers, and beseech the Lord his God, Deliver mee from bloud-guiltinesse,
Psal. 51.14. O God, thou God of my salvation. Amen. And when the Lord has heard his prayer from thence, then he comes to his Parliament, and will answere his good peoples expectation, then, and not till then; not till his people has prayed him into the deeps; and not till his prayer be heard out of the deeps: If the King comes in an orderly way to his Parliament he must passe through these deep • , he must be deeply humbled▪ he must be a man of sorrowes, he must fall low in confessions, his belly must cleave to the dust▪ even to the putting his mouth there, if there may be hope;
Lam. 3.3.29. All this will be when he is brought backe to his Parliament in a way of mercy to his poore people, and to his owne pretious soule▪ which God grant. Amen▪ Even he Lord grant that the soule of the King may be brought into the deeps for all this, and that the prayer of his soule may be answered from thence, as a poore servants prayer was answered, being in an agony and fore combate, thinking her selfe forsaken of the Lord▪ No, not forsaken, for thus shee was answered with very good words and gracious, Th •• art mine with all thy sinnes: and • and thine with all my Righteousnesse: such an answere bee to the Lord our King from the Lord. Amen and Amen.

                    Yet Sir give me leave, I pray you, for the better ventilating and winnowing the Truth, to quote Doctor Ferne once more, that we may heare how be makes good his Assertion, That the Parliament doe but pretend a defence

of the subjects liberty, they intend to invade it. These are his words;
                    The Parliaments Armies are continued, and for the maintaining of them, the liberty and property of their fellow subjects is invaded; so that if the question be put, who are those misemployed fellow subjects that these men pretend to fight against? It is plaine [as is the way of the crooked Serpent] they are such as defend their Soveraignes power, and rights, the established Religion, and government of this Church and State; their owne property and liberty. In a word, such as will not change their Soveraigne, or the established frame of government. Then the man prayes heartily, The God of power and wisedome cast out all counsels, and defeat all designes that are against the restoring of our peace, and the continuance of the rue, reformed Religion. What will you say to all this?


(5.) We say the Scorpions come flying-in upon us, here they are, and there they are, like an Adder in everie path; and now the Parliament (I meane still all the faithfull in the Land) shall be destroied: Fooles! nay vvorse then Fooles, vve are right Barbarians, no better; for our thoughts are as theirs vvere;
                        Acts 28.6. The Scorpion fastned on Pauls hand; the standers-by savv that, and they looked when Paul should have swollen, or fallen downe dead suddenly:

                        Vers. 6. These vvere Barbarians; And vvhat are vve? We see these Scorpions fastened upon the Parliaments hand; now the Parliament shall be destroied, thinke vve; our thoughts shew vvhat vve are; the Parliament shall doe now as Paul did then, they shall shake these venemous beasts off their hands into the fire, and they shall feele no harme.
